{"type":"message","id":"91a16994","parentId":"9eea3c2d","timestamp":"2026-04-12T04:41:00.239Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_38xsyrpcvqdf162oe39bdrpz","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"unique beautiful english word with meaning rare not common word of the day\",\n  \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n  \"model\": \"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n  \"tookMs\": 6731,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"content\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"78df148412823b7c\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nThe unique and beautiful English word for today, meaning rare and not common, is **Selcouth**.\\n\\n**Selcouth** (adjective)\\nPronounced: /ˈselˌkuːθ/\\n\\nMeaning: Strange, unusual, rare, or unfamiliar; also, marvelous or wondrous.\\n\\nThis archaic word comes from Old English, where \\\"seldcūth\\\" literally meant \\\"seldom known\\\" or \\\"seldom couth.\\\" It perfectly encapsulates something that is not only uncommon but also possesses an element of beauty or wonder in its rarity.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"78df148412823b7c\\\">>>\",\n  \"citations\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/selcouth\",\n      \"title\": \"merriam-webster.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/selcouth\",\n      \"title\": \"wiktionary.org\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.yourdictionary.com/selcouth\",\n      \"title\": \"yourdictionary.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.reddit.com/r/words/comments/16oh3r2/learned_a_new_archaic_word_selcouth/\",\n      \"title\": \"reddit.com\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"unique beautiful english word with meaning rare not common word of the day","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash","tookMs":6731,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"gemini","wrapped":true},"content":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"78df148412823b7c\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nThe unique and beautiful English word for today, meaning rare and not common, is **Selcouth**.\n\n**Selcouth** (adjective)\nPronounced: /ˈselˌkuːθ/\n\nMeaning: Strange, unusual, rare, or unfamiliar; also, marvelous or wondrous.\n\nThis archaic word comes from Old English, where \"seldcūth\" literally meant \"seldom known\" or \"seldom couth.\" It perfectly encapsulates something that is not only uncommon but also possesses an element of beauty or wonder in its rarity.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"78df148412823b7c\">>>","citations":[{"url":"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/selcouth","title":"merriam-webster.com"},{"url":"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/selcouth","title":"wiktionary.org"},{"url":"https://www.yourdictionary.com/selcouth","title":"yourdictionary.com"},{"url":"https://www.reddit.com/r/words/comments/16oh3r2/learned_a_new_archaic_word_selcouth/","title":"reddit.com"}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775968860219}}
